            <div type="edition" subtype="transcription" ana="b1">
                <p>Ἀρτεμίδωρος ἀνάσ<lb break="no"/>σαν ὅλης χθονὸς<lb/>Εὐδοξίαν χρυσεί<lb break="no"/>ην ἒστησε
                    περισκέ<lb break="no"/>πτῳ ἐν χώρῳ</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b1">
                <p>Artemidorus has erected the golden (statue of) Eudoxia, queen of the whole earth,
                    in a far-seen place</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" ana="b1">
                <p>The five lines are in fact two exameters worded in epic language. The Homeric
                    quotation περισκέπτῳ ἐνὶ χώρῳ is located after the caesura of the exameter as in
                    the original (Od. 1, 426; 10, 211), but whoever dictated the epigram overlooked
                    the additional iota of ἐνὶ, thus ruining the metre.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
